Nairobi residents can now breathe a sigh of relief as doctors have ended their go-slow over unpaid salaries and delayed promotions.They called off the protest on Thursday, just two days after it started.The medics protested the county government's move to deny them pay for the 100 days they were on strike from December 5 to March 14.Read: After 100 days of pain, doctors CoG and ministry cure strikeThuranira Kaugiria, Kenya Medical Practitioners, Pharmacists and Dentists&rsquo; Union Nairobi branch secretary, said the county has agreed to clear the arrears.&ldquo;We held a meeting with officials and they agreed to pay so we have no business being on the streets,&rdquo; Thuranira told The Star by phone.Governor Evans Kidero said the county is willing to pay the Sh48 million on humanitarian grounds.&ldquo;We cannot pay for work not done for the 100 days because if we do so, then it will be a contribution. But we are willing to sit with them and make ex gratia payment on humanitarian grounds,&rdquo; he told journalists at City Hall today.The doctors staged protests outside City Hall on Tuesday and Wednesday, demanding the pay and accusing the county of mistreating them.On Tuesday, Thuranira said some have not been paid since December and that deserving doctors have not been promoted, eight months after the union signed a deal with the county government.&ldquo;They have not actualised anything since we signed an agreement in November last year. Our correspondence with the governor and county secretary has borne no fruits. So we are going to protest every day until our grievances are addressed,&rdquo; he said.Kidero refuted claims that some medics have not been paid since last year. He said the only money the county had not paid was for the three months they boycotted work.On the nurses&rsquo; strike, the Governor said the county stopped the payment of negotiated allowances after advise by the Salaries and Remuneration commission.&ldquo;There was a huge discrepancy in pay under the former city council and the national government. That is why the SRC advised us to stop the payments until payments are harmonised,&rdquo; he said.More on this: Attempts to call off nurses strike thwarted as officials nearly exchange blowsAlso read: We will not renegotiate CBA, KNUN says, disapproves interns